postcontent:
-1911 22 TCM Tactical with 3 barrel 9mm conversion

The pistol is built on a double stacked frame that is designed to shoot the awesome 22 TCM round (which btw has a muzzle velocity of 2200 fps making it the most powerful handgun round in existence). The pistol is also designed to be able to fire 9mm rounds through a secondary barrel using the same magazines. The only thing that needs to happen is that the recoil spring and barrel of course need to be swapped out. 

The process takes around 3 minutes to swap out everything. 

The pistol came with a 9mm parkerized barrel however I wanted to upgrade the barrel to a 5.755 threaded chrome barrel so it was silencer ready. I can shoot within a 3 inch circle at 40 yards.

I just bought an old car i'm trying to restore and need to part with the gun for the repair work.

 I've shot around 150 rounds through the 22 TCM barrel and around 250 rounds with the chrome threaded barrel. The pistol is in fantastic shape and is only 3 months old. 

These guns are brand new on the market and I waited 6 months to buy the pistol as its Rock Island's newest and most high end pistol now.

postcontent:
DON'T waste $$$ on Steel or Bi metal rounds you cant shoot at the indoor range !!!

 Confusion over the issues of "bimetal" versus "steel core" ammo has a great deal of significance for rifle and pistol shooters because many ranges ban any bullet that responds to a magnet - especially  indoor ranges with steel backstops. title: For Trade:  Enfield No.1 Mk.III w/cutoff and 1918 Danzig Kar98a - LOOK!
postcontent:
Enfield No.1 Mk.III - 1935 - BSA Commercial - Full military config. 

Great rifle, shoots awesome. One of the rarer rifles made by BSA for other countries; EXACTLY the same as the ones issued to the British Military, just with some different stampings. Has all matching numbers including magazine. Nice stock, very good bore. Has original magazine cutoff and screw and stock disk which were purchased from IMA, as well as a sling. VERY handsome rifle. Has South African acceptance marks on top of receiver. Was going to start collecting enfields, but kind of backed off for now.


1918 Danzig Kar98a 

The second is my 1918 Danzig Kar98a. The only parts which do not match are the bolt and one of the action screws (one looks like it might match but hard to read, I'll get back on that one). Everything else matches. It was supposedly brought back by a US GI during the Battle of the Bulge in WW2, although I have no way to legitimately prove that, there is a duffel cut under the rear band which has been repaired. Something I just noticed as well is there was at some time a crack in the very end of the upper handguard but that has been fixed as well. Both of these repairs were done a long time ago; it was also refinished so I'm assuming one person did the repairs too. The rifle also has no import marks. The bore is frosted with light pitting but has a little shine and should clean up better for someone with more patience than me. I ran some patches through it and its starting to look better, like I said, my patience and attention span get the best of me sometimes. Passes bullet test with flying colors. Nice stop-gap for your collection until you can afford a really nice one. 

Trade Interests (+/- cash as necessary):
- Polish or Russian M44
- Finnish M27 or 28
- Finnish M39 Sako mfg.
- PTR91
- FAL
- Luger P38
- Beretta 92fs
- AR upper
- Madsen M47 
- Also interested in "sniperized" mosins or mausers. What do I mean by that? Rifles that are pretty much in their original wood stocks (no cut downs) and hardware, they just have a non-standard scope mount (i.e aftermarket mounts, such as a Savage 340 mount on a 91/30 or weaver bases on a mauser) or at least have the holes drilled and tapped for one. What I AM NOT looking for is your 91/30 decked out in an archangel stock with modern tacti-cool crap all over it.

Pics available upon request, I can provide HD pictures of whatever you want. I will do FTF or can ship CONUS. Contact via email or TEXT 484 - seven nine 8 - five 4 four seven.

title: For Sale:  HK Mark 23 MK23 MK 45ACP
postcontent: I don't know if you guys can tell from my auctions, but I kinda like guns. My tastes run strongly toward military guns. There aren't many of them that I can't appreciate, but there are some that really capture my attention. The HK Mark 23 is one of those. The Mark 23 is a commercial model of the government issue MK 23 MOD 0 pistol. The differences are the slide markings and that the civilian pistol barrel is manufactured to SAAMI headspace specs. This auction is for the model with two 10rd magazines. The pistol is large. If you have any problems finding a grip small enough to suit you, this pistol is not for you. If you take a look at a glock 21 and imagine the grip if the forward edge were even with the points of the finger grooves. That's the size of the HK grip. Not huge, but definitely for big hands. There's an ambidextrous thumb safety so it can be carried cocked and locked. There is also a hammer drop safety. When the thumb safety is engaged, the hammer drop can't be activated. If the thumb safety is off and the hammer drop safety is used, the thumb safety can't be engaged, and a double action trigger pull is available. It has a three white dot sight system. Front blade and rear notch are mounted in dovetails so Tritium sights can be installed easily. The rear notch sight can be adjusted to correct for windage error. The forward frame has an accessory rail. The mag release is ambi. Two drop free 10rd mags are included, along with spare barrel o-rings, a lock, a manual, and a case. The single action trigger pull is around 5 pounds and the double action around 12 pounds. The pistol is famous for it's accuracy and life. Test pistols still met the accuracy requirements after 30,000 rounds! I took plenty of photos so you can check it out. The photos were taken right out of the case so there's oil and stuff. I didn't wipe it clean first. Enjoy. I can supply the 12rd model, and spare 12 magazines or magazine kits. I will be glad to sell anywhere it's legal, doing compliance work for a reasonable amount as required. So you California, NY, and NJ shooters don't give up. I'll help you get your guns. Email me to discuss your compliance needs before you bid. If you need a payment plan, email me for the details, again before you bid please. I ship soonest for payments by US postal money order. Other money orders or anything called a check are fine with me but they sit ten business days before I ship. I know, I know, it's a bank check and you trust them. It will sit ten business days before I ship. If you want to expedite the overall transaction, send the US PMO for your final payment. By the way, things are slowed down due to the work overload caused by the gun buying activity. I work long hours doing the best I'm able. That's all I offer you. If you need quicker than the soonest I'm able, you should be buying elsewhere. I'm proud of you Americans for arming yourselves. I pray that THE God supreme intends it for our deliverance and not for our destruction. I can't take credit or debit cards. I won't do business with anti-gun PayPal and neither should you. Look where we are as a nation. If the people had hung the politicians and lawyers sooner, we would be in much better shape. Separate yourself from those who are doing wrong to our country and stand up for our heritage. Today's people do NOT have the right to change America. This was founded a republic not a mobocracy. You'll pay me about what UPS charges me for shipping. Email me if you have questions. Thanks for checking out my auctions. Cheers!

location: Dayton's Bluff, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
Up for grabs is a very unique gun. Only 40,000 of these were ever made and I'm sure not too many of those survive. It shoots .380 ACP and shoots well, as it has a very smooth action. It has a really unique release for cleaning that is a breeze to operate. The gun is extremely clean for its age.

Feel free to text me or call me at six12 two24 5245 for more info or to come see the gun. As always, you'll need a PTP or PTC in order to purchase this from me.

Here's more info on the gun:

Type	Double Action Only semiautomatic
Caliber(s)	 9x17 Browning Short
Weight unloaded	980 g
Length	190 mm
Barrel length	118 mm
Magazine capacity	9 rounds



The CZ Vz.38 pistol, also sometimes referred to simply as CZ-38, was developed in 1937 in an attempt to fullfil requirements, issued by Czechoslovak army, for a sidearm which would be more safe and simple  to handle than previously used CZ Vz.24. New gun was designed by Frantisek Myska, and submitted to military trials early in 1938. After trials, which were consdered sucessful, Czechoslovak army ordered significant numbers of these pistols, but Germans took over the Czechoslovakia before any guns could be delivered. A few guns were delivered to Bulgaria in 1939, but  the rest of the production (about 10 000 guns) was consumed by German police and security forces. Production of this gun has ceased by the end of WW2, and was never resumed later. This is not surprising, as the gun was overly big and heavy for the cartridge it used (9mm Browning Short, also known as 9mm Kurz or .380 ACP). Also, the double action only trigger was too heavy, severely impairing accuracy of fire.

The CZ Vz.38 pistol is a simple blowback operated weapon. It is unusual as its barrel at the muzzle is mounted in the special bushing, which in turn is hinged to the frame. Upon the disassembly, operator pulls back the dismounting slide, located on the left side of the frame, then pulls the rear of the slide up. This causes the barrel and slide to rotate up around the axis, located below the muzzle, and also disengages the slide from return spring, which is located in the frame below the barrel. Once the rear part of the slide is clear off the frame, slide can be bulled back and slid off the barrel. This allows for easy diassembly, cleaning and examination of the barrel bore. The trigger is of double action only type, with external hammer. No manual safeties are provided by default (export Bulgarian version had additional manual safety on the left side of the frame). Magazine is of single stack type, magazine release catch is located at the base of the grip.
